{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"62a7e6f1-7d0c-40c6-beb4-1780f409132f","content":"You can download `dotnet-trace` as a **self-contained binary** — no SDK required:\n\n```bash\n# From inside the container:\ncurl -sSL https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-x64 -o dotnet-trace\nchmod +x ./dotnet-trace\n\n# Collect a CPU trace (replace <PID> with your app's process ID)\n./dotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\n**Other options:**\n\n- **ARM64 containers:** use `https://aka.ms/dotnet-trace/linux-arm64`\n- **Copy from host:** download locally, then `docker cp dotnet-trace <container>:/tmp/`\n- **Find the PID:** run `ps aux | grep dotnet` or use `./dotnet-trace ps`\n\nThe output `.nettrace` file can be copied out (`docker cp`) and opened in Visual Studio, PerfView, or [Speedscope](https://www.speedscope.app).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9d0c1c3a-81e4-410b-a1ba-f1d77b77ef5d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to get `dotnet-trace` into a Linux container that doesn't have the .NET SDK installed. This is a common diagnostic scenario for .NET applications. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of .NET diagnostics tools.\n\nThe key approaches are:\n1. Download `dotnet-trace` as a .NET global tool (requires SDK)\n2. Download it as a standalone/self-contained binary (no SDK needed)\n\nSince they don't have the SDK, the answer is to use the standalone download approach via the `dotnet-install` script or direct download of the self-contained version.","outputTokens":393,"requestId":"C3CD:C42E6:1D3D0C1:20D5108:6A07C35C"},"id":"33a632f5-231f-4fc4-a381-021486b8aba0","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:07:49.502Z","parentId":"81123759-7aad-4d11-a88a-522e9d79f5f2"}
